<section id="Box30"> <h2>Day 30 DWC: 2017-04-30 Sunday</h2> </section> <h3>POSH</h3> <H5>Css tabs</h5>

<p>
Thinking about where to go after the 30 Day writing challenge took me to 

reading <a href="https://adaptivewebdesign.info/">Adaptive Web Design by 

Aaron Gustavson</a>
</p>
<p>
He talks the difference between progressive enhancement and graceful 

degradation and clarifies the importance of accessibility on all kinds of 

devices. I find the analogy of an M&M's to highlight the layers of content 

very useful.
</p>
<ul>
<li>Peanut (html): kernel or nugget of content</li>
<li>Chocolate(css): tasty attractive covering </li>
<li>Shell sugar coating(JavaScript): unique entertaining interactions.</li>
</ul>
 
<p>
It encouraged me to think about how to continue with development of the site 

and keep up a writing habit.
</p>
<p>
Looking for some easy guidelines I found <a href="https://www.sitepoint.com/progressive-enhancement-1-html/">Progressive Enhancement Techniques</a> by  Craig Buckler at SitePoint.
</P> 
<p> 
Three articles covering html, css and Javascript applied progressively.
<br>
Introducing some tabs seems like a good idea to navigate to different parts of the page.
<br>
I stuck to content and style for now with just one line of script.

<p>
I still have a lot to learn about POSH 'Plain Old Semantic Html' and 

writing straight into a text editor as markup I have found useful practice over the 

month.
</P>
<p>
Using<a href="https://validator.w3.org"> Nu Html Checker </a> 

before updating the page is a little win if I find I have written the code without 

errors. 
</p>

