<section id="Box28"> <h2>Day 28 DWC: 2017-04-28 Friday</h2> </section> <h3>Informed Technology</h3> <H5>Chronology</h5> 

<p>
First decade: the 1960's
<br>
<br>
A black and white TV  I watched a cycling race.  
<br>
A bicycle with stabilisers.   I rode it without them on a garden lawn.
<br>
<br>
Two tin cans joined by string.  Listening to my sister in another room.
<br>
A  telephone,  three numbers carefully dialled to hear my granny's voice.
<br>
A transistor radio with an earplug.  I listened to pop music. Broadcast from a boat off the English coast.
<br>
My dads scooter had a windshield.  He would take me on the back and we'd go for a walk and talk about wildflowers and insects.
<br>
At school  a record player and a black and white TV.
In class we listened and learned the patterns and danced to English country tunes. Heard the poetry of Dylan Thomas and watched a man walk on the moon.
<br>
Learned writing with wooden leaded pencils and a rubber, colourful wax crayons then a fountain pen with scented blue ink and blotting paper.
And painting with round blocks of water paint on coloured sugar paper.
</p>

<ul>
  <li>
Plain white paper exercise books for drawing, 
  </li>
  <li>
Lined white paper exercise books for writing. 
  </li>
  <li>
 Squared white paper for maths. 
  </li>
  <li>
Another squared paper with smaller squares for graphs.
</li>
<li>
  Five lined paper to write musical notes, tunes for a woodwind recorder. 
</li>
</ul>
Lots of different kinds of paper.
<br>
Lots of books with pictures.

<p>
Second decade: the 1970's
<br>
<br>
A record player in a wooden box like a suitcase with  snap catches, a carrying handle and two coloured vinyl faux leather surface. A tall center post with a catch to balance several records, and an arm to hold them in place to be released automatically with mechanical precision timing.
<br>
Singles, 45's the most popular one of the week and the top ten were frequently discussed.  There were magazines that published the lyrics.
<br>
A black bicycle, no gears, curved handlebars, rattly mudgards and a basket on the front. a mode of transport to travel round the country lanes to learn crafting skills at village hall workshops.
<br>
LP's. Albums played for hours with coloured arty sleeves.  Inner protective sleeves.  If they slid out the things would crack.  Or on a sunny windowsill, go soft and buckle into wavy bumps. Scratchy interference on playback was the norm for favoured well worn discs.
<br>
At school a room full of typewriters.  Typing a commerce lesson commerce. Noisy and smelled of ribbon ink and typewriter oil.
<br>
A language lab. Cubicles surrounded by grey painted hardboard covered in holes.  Heavy plastic headphones speaking French.  A tape recorder that could be stopped and started and spoken to.
<br>
And a room full of sewing machines. A foot pedal to make neat roads of seams. Guiding cloth under shiny steel feet and sharp bobbing needle speed a blur.
<br>
A colour television. Three channels. Shared and  watched in the evening.  A  picture with a clown and repeating muzak broadcast during the day, for technicians and repairs.
<br>
Motorbikes and discos and live punk bands in the ballroom.  Electric guitars and smoke machines and glitterballs.
<br>
I rode an automatic moped. And passed a test to drive a car.


</p>
<p>
Third decade: the 1980's.
<br>
<br>
Typewriters electric, audio typing. Dictation machines replayed voices to be typed.  How to type in boxes, forms counting the even spaces of type. Making dots and joining them. Spinning golf ball typewriter. Shuttling crazy faster than the fingers could go.  A lighter touch, or the letters would multiply 
<br>
Microprocessor awareness.
<br>
First punch cards, ticker tape with little square holes, reams of it. And printouts of green lined paper with holes down the sides.  The paper came out fast.  It could print out astrological predictions in no time. If you knew your star sign.
<br>
Programming lessons on an Apple Macintosh.  And an IBM Tandy RadioShack. There were strings and dollar signs and dots and brackets. Code.  Luminous green on a dark screen. Platform games and Pong in pubs.  Waves of asteroids to blast out of electronic sky on a table screen set in fake laminated wood.
<br>
Then lazers.  Beams of light reaching the moon. Accurately meauring the distance from an old castle that kept the ships log of Captain Cook.
The faint spidery sepia handwriting fading tidily into yellowing leather bound pages.
Speeding through space and back, tiny lights, brightly carving rainbow disc colours on metal foil.
<br>
Photocopiers. Micro chips. Microprocessors.  Word processors. Spreadsheets.  One or two PC's. Novelty at first.  The huge buildings quiet humming concrete and glass with efficient workers gliding knowingly.  Lighting streets at night.  Went dark. 
<br>
Small businesses sprang up
<br>
There was talk of catalitic converters.
</p>
<p>
Fourth decade. The 1990's 
<br>
<br>
Modems garbled messages down phonelines screeching whirring dial up.  
<br>
Ms dos then windows.
<br>
Mice.
<br>

Children played games with pixels channelled through cassette tapes.  
<br>
Teenagers recorded music on them.
<br>
The TV could be taped.  On BetaMax or VHS.
<br>
 Magnetic tape. 
<br>
 Films could be bought to watch at home or rented, there were shops and libraries of them.  And special offers at petrol stations.
<br>
Then CD's for music and DVD's for film. Bright rainbow discs that didn't mind a scratch or two, but sometimes skipped or didn't work at all.  Hard and shiny in plastic cases. 
<br>
Micro wave ovens and dimmer switches.  Electrical goods ... 
<br>
Pagers sending text.  
</p>
<p>
Fifth decade: Y2k
<br>
<br>
Anxiety that viruses would eat up all the data destroy machines.  Anti virus software and subscriptions.
<br>
PC publishing. And Photoshop.  Digital photography.
<br>
phishing
<br>
An old PC with a one gig hard drive. No USB. Double speed cd ROM.  Discs on magazines to try out software, shareware, freeware. Malware. Spyware. Tutorials. Games.
<br>
The hard drive went.
<br>
Lots of big thick paperback manuals.
Fascinating screensavers to protect the chunky ray tube monitor.
<br>
Then flat screens. LCD or LED.  Digital TV with a set top box, no more analogue. And oh yes records now called vinyl. Or satellite.  Multi-multi channels.  Subscription or diy free view?  Satellite internet?
Fiber optic cables.
<br>
A laptop
<br>
Corel draw essentials.  
Digital painting and vector graphics.  Photo manipulation.  Pixel perfect. Electronic digital camera, rechargeable batteries.
<br>
Touchpad.
<br>
Sounds, mp3 files.  Mp3 players. Shuffle. Libraries piracy and play.
<br>
An interactive encyclopedia on a cd ROM.
<br>
A netbook and a dongle and another lost hard drive.
<br>
Role play games - anonymity, handles and forums and FAQ.  
<br>
Microwave towers.
<br>
It worked quire well for a while then broke.  Loud beeping noises and refused to start up.
</p>
<p>
A peek into decade 6.  The 2010's.
<br>
<br>
A smartphone with no manual.  A data plan. Tapping sliding icons.  A portable amusement arcade.
<br>
Words with friends and Facebook. Tsu and Tower of Saviours. Walking to portals with a battery booster. Sound recording, playback.  Photos, editing, cloud storage - instagram the selfie!
<br>
Maps and information, books. Speech to text
Poor battery life and broken WiFi.
<br>
One plus one android.  
Screen,  keyboard, sim, sound recorder, speakers camera.  
<br>
Flash.
<br>
Clock, calendar
<br>
TV, Music, University, Social.
<br>
Car charger.
<br>
Shared.
<br>
Listicles
<br>
Writing
<br>
Poems
<br>
Code
<br>
Post post modern 
<br>
steam punk 
<br>
fragments.  
<br>
Who are the consumers.  
<br>
What is the user story.  
<br>
Where is the product.
</p>
<p>
On the way to my wifi connection the car radio tuned into Heart was played <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XfR9iY5y94s"> Men at Work </a>

<section id="Box27"> <h2>Day 27 DWC: 2017-04-26 Thursday</h2> </section> <h3>Civilisation</h3> <H5>Blue Plastic</h5>
<p>
Arctic blue, the sky is blowing from the north. white clouds spaced neatly have bubbling  tops like avalanche snow and completely smooth grey flat bases.  A shear layer like the surface of some polar icy water.  The clouds are snowballs floating on an ocean, a flock of them, a shoal, something, a kind of gathering or migration.  Floating across the sky.  Uniform or regimental in their similarity, patterned copies they look smaller in the distance, my sense of perspective telling me they're all the same size. Drifting south, wave after wave advancing.
</p>
<p>
Ahead a wooded slope, or could I call it forested.  Multicoloured hues and shades of trees in Spring.  The rounded  mottled and variegated domes  of summer leaved trees sap surging through their twigs surround a  rectanglular block of dark pines.  A great eagle's broad dark shadow swoops and wheels turning in flight to glide down towards some watery expanse I know hidden amongst the hyperboreal wasteland.
</p>
<p>
As the little tufts of dwarf gorse flowers darken and fade  bright lemony peaflower shapes are sprinkled amongst a swathe of broom shoots. Bare patches of white sandy soil have a papery crust that matches the drying bark on a pile of corded birch logs. Now after nearly a month without rain  roots have extracted all moisture, but made use of every drop, to flaunt foliage and to catch the sun.
</p>
<p>
The tawny horses with the blonde highlights in their manes and the primitive splotchy markings on their legs are nibbling bramble shoots in a glade of fine woodland grass and rush, the delicate sward cushioned with thick moss is soft underfoot.  Crunchy litter drifted into heaps in shade startles them and dry snapping twigs.  They watch, ears pricked forward, curious,  alert,  amiable.
</p>
<p>
Past where the wild boar rootle leaving peeled back turf. Through scrubby saplings and windblown rootstumps is an iron digging fork. Patches of paint and a bloom of rust on tines half speared into the ground, wooden handle snapped off, a label still intact on the shaft.   Dog and bull.  Humans words in an oval logo conjure images of animals.
</p>
<p>
By the entance to the growing field of best pony hay was a little black bag, knotted, hanging limply on a blackthorn bush. 
</p>
<p>
Up the straight and narrow path a little way in front of me, a bright blue plastic bag, like a piece of that arctic sky triangular and weighted in one hand of a gentleman with a tweed brown cap.

Grey fleece, new navy jeans and trainers he was keeping the same pace. 
</p>
<p>
Into the lane where cars pass by I turned to go the opposite way.  
</p>
<p>
He called, "Missy".  
</p>
<p>
"Can you tell me where I am? - Which way to go? - Where there's a place?" 
</p>
<p>
Tanned with toothy gaps and round eyes pale.  Blue irises, black pupils restlessly searching, scanning the shrubby undergrowth and verdant hedgerows.
</p>
<p>
I walked with him through the bluebell wood mauve perfume wafting in pockets through the twisting mossy hornbeam trees. 
</p>
<p>
"When will we be out of this National lottery forest?"  
</p>
<p>
Past some light brown curly furred cows with calves beside a nook of brakeny gorse. And hawthorn its creamy flowers just starting to show. The cows stood looking at us, backlit, the sinking sun flashing halos of their bovine shape. Starting to set in the west behind a Norman towered stone church nestled on a wooded brow.
</p>
<p>
As we approached the village he spoke. 
</p>
<p>
"What's that word? - That long word?"
</p>
<p>
" Civilisation?" I suggest.
</p>
<p>
"Yes, that's the one." He grinned and laughed.
</p>
<p>
Emerging from a rough and bumpy track onto the street a smooth two-way road paved on either side with footpaths and kirbstones and short mown narrow strips of lawn. Straight ahead across the road, a construction site, dusty, great earth moving machines surrounded by tall metal barriers hung with colored notices. Placards. Boards. Crowded on a pole. Hoardings.
</p>
<p>
"I know that" he said, stretching out his arm and pointing.
</p>
<p>
He took out a blue metal can from his blue plastic bag, snapped off the ring pull and took a sip.  
</p>
<p>
We shook hands and parted ways.
</p>
<section id="Box26"> <h2>Day 26 DWC: 2017-04-26 Wednesday</h2> </section> <h3>Mindfulness</h3> <H5>Bodyscan</h5> 

<p>
Sitting quietly upright on a sapphire blue cloth chair.
</p>
<p>
Soft black headphones on my ears, their twisty matt black finely ridged double melded cable winds over my knee through the dancing sun light and leaf shadows, glinting gold where the jack plugs into the steel rimmed phone.
</p>
<p>
Finding an mp3 file, black and orange like a bullseye target icon, I  open it with a headphone icon to reveal a  rectangular sound box with an arrow and a slider button.  Underneath are two words.  Bodyscan unknown.  I press play and close my eyes.  A calm and steady male voice speaks, stutters jankily.
</p>
<p>
Looking at the screen two small bold pause pillars on the right jitter on and off.  Playing with the sunshine shadows.  I quickly touch the tiny pillars vibrating  breakbeat morse code with my thumb and a small black triangle appears pointing west.  
</p>
<p>
I touch the triangle behind the shiny glass screen.  The voice is smooth and steady this time.  Closing my eyes I listen and breath in.  Imagining my body filled with air.  And out, and in again. The morning air is cool, it feels good.
</p>
<p>
The voice guides my attention to my right big toe.  Wiggling it I feel the inside of my shoe.  And then the other toe, the left one.  Focussing on them now both big toes together.  Breathing a slow rhythm.  Feeling the air in my toes. Then the little toes back and forth, my attention.  
</p>
<p>
Curious now I notice the toes in between the big and little toes seem to feel a bit less.  Together they act as one.  More of a group than individuals.  Little pads in contact with the ground neatly tucked together arched down nails.  I wonder if this is how it feels - a cats paw.  Or to extend that feeling even into one toe, as horses do finger bones stretched and fused together. That middle toe extending, hardening into one sturdy hoof.
</p>
<p>
I didn't think about paws when I was focussed on my toes. that arose just now as I go back over it and write.  And I remember how the skeletons of animals are similar but different.  From diagrams in books.  In black and white.  This is the structure.  A skeletal system.
</p>
<p>
I wasn't really feeling much of my bone structure, more the sensations on my skin or in the muscles as I journeyed around my body.  Steadily, not hurried.  Legs and back.  Shoulders, hands and arms. Neck, mouth eyes.  The breath still cool and rhythmic.  Moving eyebrows, forehead, scalp.  I stretch wriggle my ears, they're getting cramped now, a bit squashed under the headphones.
</p>
<p>
The recorded voice suggests I slowly open my eyes let in light and take in the surroundings.  Not yet.  There's too much of it.  Too many possibilities.  I'll rush and start to do things.  The things will be compelling. There's loads of stuff needs doing. 
</p>
<p>
So for now I keep the headphones on and write.  Focus on the black mirror keyboard and the white box text.  Bring out some words to describe it.  Go over what I did.  OK.  Enough.  (550 words, 2 minutes to read) My shoulders have started aching my feet are cold and the other stuff that needs doing calls as the sun is warm on my cheek.
</p>






<section id="Box25"> <h2>Day 25 DWC: 2017-04-25 Tuesday</h2> </section> <h3>Shrine</h3> <H5>On the Village Green</h5>

<p>
In the center of the village is a small  square building like a shrine.  
Open sided four sandstone pillars made with curved blocks, 
the soft mellow coloured stone has paler thick mortar in between, and is faintly criss-cross carved with
indecipherable letters and signs.
</p>
<p>  
The pillars support a red-baked tile roof. Half way up the roof slope becomes four cream painted 
flat triangles with a symmetrical cross shaped ridge.  A kind of four sided turret. Then a plinth like 
a curved vase, or concrete bollard.  A wrought iron weather vane with dark spirals points North against
a cold blue sky. 
</p>
<section id="Box24"> <h2>Day 24 DWC: 2017-04-24 Monday</h2> </section> <h3>Internet of Plants</h3> <H5>The Common Mycelial Network</h5> 

<p>
There is an Internet of Plants, a fungal web called the Common Mycelial Network or CMN.  A communication  network of chemical and electrical signals.
</p>
<p>
Mycorrhizal mycelium are the cobwebby component of fungi.  Spreading through soil their fine filaments and  tiny threads form matrix mats and complex networks.  Myriad entries into plant roots form connections and pathways.  This is the infrastructure.
</p>
<p>
Within the mycelium many complex activities of fungi occur.  The transfer of nutrients from soil to plant along these fungal networks is known to be a crucial part of healthy a ecosystem.  Once established they become  'Network-enhanced bioactive zones'. More here on <a href="http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/nph.13115/full">Interplant Signalling through Hyphal Networks</a> at the New Phytologist.
</p>
<p>
This Common Mycelial Network is also a communication network.  Chemical and electrical signals sent along these fungal pathways alert plants to damage and attack by insects and other herbivores or plant damaging fungi.  The plants can then respond defensively by releasing chemicals that repel their attackers.
</p>
<p>
A  symbiosis, hard to study is secretly concealed within the soil.  Delicate and intricate at  its microscopic scale, yet extensive and rapid to adapt and grow and change. Resilient in transformative ways to  fluctuations.
</p>
<p>
It's important that we try to protect and understand our established healthy ecosystems.  Link them, find out what they need, learn to appreciate their beauty and functionality and how to value it.  
</p>
<p>
Why is having a coherent and resilient ecological network important?  This report goes into some detail for findings in the UK.
<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/making-space-for-nature-a-review-of-englands-wildlife-sites-published-today">Making Space for Nature</a>
</p>


<section id="Box23"> <h2>Day 23 DWC: 2017-04-23 Sunday</h2> </section> <h3>Earth Day</h3> <H5>Homo Sapiens and Horses</h5> 

<p>
The day before yesterday I finished reading <a href="https://books.google.de/books/about/Sapiens.html?id=FmyBAwAAQBAJ">Sapiens: A brief History of Humankind by Yuval Noah Harari</a>.  A hardback book my dad lent me  it's got a nice white paper cover with an embossed black fingerprint on the front, tactile, like brail but with a smoothly contoured slightly rubbery plastic feel.. As Ive been doing this writing challenge I've been reading the book, usually a chapter a day.  The fingerprint  is a good motif for the theme of the marks we humans make that runs through the book.  A symbolic representation of the fluid contours of our history, a map as all good story books have, to imprint on the mind as a delineated guide.
</p>
<p>
Deliberately  not hurrying is a habit I'm learning to appreciate.  The small chunks of <a href="https://books.google.de/books?id=iPDUDAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=daily+stoic&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjH2_rF-7rTAhXpA8AKHcskAkcQ6AEIKzAB#v=onepage&q=daily%20stoic&f=false">Daily Stoic</a> have set the tone for this.  I'm changing a tendency to rush through books absorbing as much as possible quickly, cramming, skimming over the words to get the gist and a comprehensive overview. Writing myself is helping me appreciate more the arrangement of the words and structure, cadence - quality.
</p>
<p>
So I purchased a new ebook to read with a £3 token and rewards from Google surveys.   <a href="https://books.google.de/books?id=9sZ1CwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Horses,+horses&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjXvMvh_LrTAhXEfFAKHY8fCMUQ6AEIIjAA#v=onepage&q=Horses%2C%20horses&f=falseHorses,"> Horses, Horses, in the End the Light Remains Pure.</a>  I've wanted to read it since about a year ago.  It's going to be hard and I need to be brave.  I don't want to feel sad.  What I remember is that it's about Fukushima which is a region of Japan famed for its horses, by a Japanese novelist who grew up there, moved away, then had to go back, after the tsunami disaster 3/11  to see for himself.
</p>
<p>
Through the month of March 2011 I watched the newsreels sending footage, over and over, each installment another horrifying display of things that couldn't be.
</p>
<p>
The tsunami from above and then the power plant, fixed cameras focused on boxes, cubes against  blue sky.  Waiting.  The news already happened.  That was then.  And I don't have a television set any more.
</p>
<p>
Yesterday was Earth Day I liked the animated Google doodle that told me so and I tried the new <a href="https://earth.google.com/web/@0,0,-24018.82718741a,36750128.22569847d,35y,0h,0t,0r/data=CgAoAQ">Google Earth</a> app on my phone.  'Feeling Lucky' I let Google choose.  It zoomed me round the world to a city in Japan called Minamiaizu.  OK.  I stroked a finger around the screen, widened out to read the writing, Japanese and English.  Across and up the Eastern Pacific coast beside dark shadows in the sea - tectonic forces. To Soma, a place of horses.
</p>
<p>
And Fukushima to my surprise is inland and a city.
</p>
<p>
I visit Tokyo,  a grey brown intricacy in daylight from above.  Different to the brightly neon coloured street scenes I recollect, cartoons and cables with drifting saloon cars in Grand Theft Auto style Vice city  - with cherry blossom. 
</p>
<p>
Then Hiroshima, which seems to be a forest.  A dark green bobbly textured blanket.  Japan does have a lot of trees. 
</P>
<p>
I looked at some MOOC's offered by UTokyoX University, and signed up for one with EdX called <a href="https://education-and-growth.blogspot.co.uk/2017/03/sustainability-science-key-concept-for.html">Sustainability Science - A Key Concept for Future Design.</a> They also offer courses on radiation and quantum mechanics which look interesting and more on another platform which  I've not tried.  
</P>
<p>
I then read a bit on Wikipedia about native Japanese ponies which led to an interesting UN Food and Agriculture Organisation report <a href="http://www.fao.org/docrep/010/a1250e/a1250e00.htm">The State of the World's Animal Genetic Resources for Food and Agriculture...</a>
</p>
<p>
Earth Day was also the start of a three year campaign to increase environmental literacy by the <a href="http://www.earthday.org/2017/02/20/earth-day-network-launches-three-year-campaign-environmental-climate-literacy-earth-day-2017/">Earth Day Network (EDN) </a>
</p>


<section id="Box22"> <h2>Day 22 DWC: 2017-04-22 Saturday</h2> </section> <h3>White Mare</h3> <H5>... and a baby robin</h5> 
<p>
The flank of a white mare, dappled grey, the sky.  Vision of a newborn foal, that whiteness overhead.  Beneath a green dome stretching away of salad plant life to chew, so fresh in May.  Scent of mowed grass scythed by toothy blades and trodden lightly with the curved rim hooves. And warm milk, comforting and safe.  Mother kind, attentive, softly nuzzles, nudges,  pleased to show her little one the way.
</p>
<p>
Lying flat on the grass chin cupped in hands I gaze. One soft brown eye looks at me shining through white lashes while she grazes.  Can I see the whorl that gathers to a spiral on her forehead.  A subtle flashing and pulsating optic swirl emerging - or am I blind.
</p>
<p>
Or the colour of down at the base of a rock doves feather.  Soft light, gentle on the eyes. Thick floral aroma carries  euphoria in the cool air which glows green.  Not bioluminescence but sunlight, diffused refractionally, blended, not electrically, but pure.  Into the chlorophyll to glow back yellow green.  A delicate flux and an intricate activity of complexity.
</p>
<p>
The sleeping bag on my knee is microfiber and machine stitched, its crinkled puffy folds and shadows are half grey, the colour of silver coins without the shine and that yellow green, the colour of young maple leaves.  Sitting by an open door, a net drawn back to feel the air and smell the trees my eyes are closed in mindful contemplation.
</p>
<p>
A drumming flutter and a tiny brush of cool air wafts my hand.  Cautiously I part the lids of just one closed eye a tiny bit.  Sitting on my knee, facing the brightness of the world through the open door, wide eyes glistening, a fluffy baby robin.
</p>

<section id="Box21"> <h2>Day 21 DWC: 2017-04-21 Friday</h2> </section> <h3>New buds moon</h3> <H5>A willow month</h5> 

<p>
Everything is green. Overwhelmingly green.  This year is dry the April showers have been meagre so far.  An occasional sprinkling in the night which by morning leaves no trace but for an extra burst of growth and lushness. 
</p>
<p>
Oak tree flowers adorn majestically spreading branches putting into shadow gnarly moss encrusted bark.  Each one's display glows a slightly different hue, some orange others yellow lime.  Twigs look black against the sky and the catkins rustle to slight wafts of breeze.  Baby birds earnestly practicing agility whilst cheeping loud simple notes are absorbed in climbing higher. Explorers of the air,  their feathers sprouting faster than the greens. 
</p>
<p>
 Little robins, tawny brown emergent from the dark evergreen dusty ivy tree.  Its  twisting clambering trunk hugging sprawl  and shag pile bark a place to start that spark of life as they chipped their way through warm  shell, compelled, to find the light.  To leave that smooth round moss lined nest so carefully crafted and kept clean.  The soft down and tender care, the excitement and energy of insect foods.
</p>
<p>
Below a purple haze of violet blue contrasts with green.  Bluebells coyly curving from spear like buds  unfurling. In simultaneous release the coiled back petals send a scent so heady it overpowers the rankness of thick layers of leaf mould and moss and mushrooms.  The wood hyacinth of the Weald casts its enchanting spell amid the dapple of spreading oak flower, soft winglike leaves of hazel copse entwined with honeysuckle woodbine. 
</p>
<p>
 Sunken meandery lane banks topped with dense trimmed hedge of hornbeam, hawthorn and now and then wild cherries. Airy white petals for a moment showing off their difference bright amongst the myriad twigs then done so gently drifting. In these hollows in this new buds moon floral scents linger louder even than car exhaust fumes and warm tarmac.
</p>
<p>  
Will and sally  in a garden, cats paws and goats beards, the ground is dotted with soft things, everywhere rabbit tail shapes littering.  A watery woodland cracked chaotic.  Not a tidy place.  Soft soil doesn't hold their roots well in gales so some have fallen gently, others snapped and broke.  But the branches, often when they hit the ground sprout feeding feelers almost instantly.  Sustained  by iron stained stream water they become crowded baskets.
</p>

<section id="Box20"> <h2>Day 20 DWC: 2017-04-20 Thursday</h2> </section> <h3>Sheep</h3>
<h5>In a turnip field</h5> 

<p>
As the tree shadows lengthened and the suns rays mellowed into a golden evening light I leant on a galvanised gate overlooking a turnip field dotted with a flock of sheep.
</p>
<p>
The sheep baa-ed intermittently calling out to one another, a motely mix, some with black faces. Others with white shaggy top notches and some with tiny lambs racing and bounding in play.
</p>
<p>
Some were nibbling the dry turnips that had thick woody stems taller than the sheep themselves, others were browsing short grasses and bramble from around the field edges and woodland hedge.
</p>
<p>
One or two nearby looked back at me quizzically.
</p>
<section id="Box19"> <h2>Day 19 DWC: 2017-04-19 Wednesday</h2> </section> <h3>Fallow </h3> 
<h5>An uncultivated plot.</h5> 
<p>
The practice of leaving land to rest and regenerate.
</p>
<p>
It seems that about a third of cultivated land was left fallow in carefully documented medieval times.   People in the UK divided land between themselves in furlong strips for growing food crops for themselves as well as for livestock.
</p>
<p>  
A swift internet search reveals that uncultivated plots are unpopular amongst allotment holders and some of the regulations are quite intolerant of a lack of cultivation of plots which  is viewed as a problem. The  communal cultivation of urban allotments  has some parallels with earlier types of farming and land use but not in the area of intentionally leaving them fallow.
</p>
<section id="Box18"> <h2>Day 18 DWC: 2017-04-18 Tuesday</h2> </section> <h3>Horses on the heath</h3> <H5>Step back in time</h5> 
<p>
A descent from a sharp corner on a wooded lane into an open expanse of undulating fields with tree lined gullies.  The step back in time field is an ancient track. Buried beneath open grassland and a steady incline of about half a mile it echoes with the chattering of people engaged in showing off their old agricultural machinery.
</p>
<p>
For several years an August weekend would be busy with bustle and diesel fumes as crowds stopped by to wander around curiously perusing all manner of strange implements and tools, watched as wattles were crafted, hop poles erected and a shire horse protected her new foal in a pen. Heavy horses and small clattering tractors ploughed and tilled small patches of soil, energetically demonstrating a variety of bygone country skills.
</p>
<p>
Now the fields are quiet, the sheep who grazed over the winter have gone.  Skylark  song pierces the  breeze as if signalling it's found an unexpected area of downland in this densely wooded Weald.
</p>
<p>
The track goes into the wood beside scrubby bushes and bramble.  Rough bricks and tiles, lumps of sandstone and old iron working smelt protrude like a mini mountain range down the centre, cemented into the dark dry mud.  
</p>
<p>
The musical gurgling of a fast flowing stream with high sided mossy banks thick with clumps of golden saxifrage and the garlicky smell of ransome's, resonates as it passes through an old red brick arched culvert to join another stream.  The slightly clouded water glints with dancing sun rays sparkling through the gloom, gliding over blackened gravel, swirling fallen hazel lambs tails in pools dammed by broken sticks and leaves.
</p>
<p>
The ancient track climbs, a curvy, double tyre tread pattern kept ley line straight, on course, a steady up, then down, then higher still to a beacon. Meanwhile the stream meanders downwards this way and that exposing  pale clay as it turns into some tall pines. Telegraph poles alive, who instead of wires wear dark green tufts of needles high up on their spindly branches, and are filled with the sweet high notes of tiny birds flitting around invisibly.
</p>
<p>
Are the horses in the broom forest?  Where can they be.  They hide there sometimes and are hard to find.  A south facing hillside.  A few years back a larch plantation is now a heathland wood pasture. Heather, birch and broom, soft fine grasses diligently cropped.
A tiny orange butterfly on a flower.  Buzzards shrieking, wheel and soar, arguing they flap and interact like kids who play on bikes.
</p>
<p>
The horses are in the meadow, beyond the cart track puddle filled with tadpoles, below the orchard with the deer hide platform and the beehives. An old crab apple still bearing tiny red apples is just starting to blossom.
</p>

