<h3>CSS, GitHub and marking off the Days</h3>
<H5>Incrementally keeping it minimal</h5>
<p>Writing straight into the html document today or I would probably keep tinkering with the code and not do the writing.</p>
<p>Tentatively added some styles this morning, and keeping them in the head of the document the whole thing is still just one file.  Mostly experimenting with body elements, changing the font style and weight,
and adding some colour.  I got very distracted choosing colours, it's absorbing fun, so easy to do.  Still what I set out to do
was change the width so the text is easier to read on a large screen.  Coding it on the phone makes it easy to forget the width as 
automatically filling the screen looks fine on a narrow one.</p>

<p>I didn't like the look of the the X in the calendar boxes and decided that as the boxes change colour anyway when I link them to the writing
they don't need to be there.</p>
<p>The calendar template itself is good though and and I'm happy with the way its turning out.</p> 
<p>I'm thinking about making another one along similar lines for 100 and 301 days of code.  I spent quite a while sorting out the days
for 100 days of code in the GitHub repo as I'd gone adrift with them somewhere in the 60's.  I thought I was nearly at day 100 indeed I tweeted day 95
yesterday and I'm in fact on day 105.  10 days out! </p>
<p>Seeing the page on a larger screen makes the fonts look too big, also I shall look into a different types. But for now I'll let it settle and have another look tomorrow.</p> 

<section id="Box15">
<h2>Day 15 DWC: 2017-04-15 Saturday</h2>
</section>
<h3>Let's talk about Nitrogen</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><b>What is it?</b>  It is a common chemical element in the universe. It is estimated at about seventh in total abundance in the Milky Way and the Solar System.  
	                  The majority of earth's atmosphere (78%) is nitrogen.</li>
	    
    <li><b>Where is it?</b>  Being such a large part of the earths atmosphere nitrogen is literally everywhere. 
	                  A building block of proteins and nucleic acids such as DNA, a crucially important component of all biological
					  life. The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nitrogen_cycle#/media/File:Nitrogen_Cycle.svg">nitrogen cycle</a> is a complex biogeochemical 
					  cycle in which nitrogen is converted from its inert atmospheric molecular form (N2) into a form that 
					  is useful in biological processes. </li>
					  
    <li><b>Why we should know about it.</b> It is the most significant part of earth's ecosystems and collective human activities like industry and agriculture
	                  are having a massive impact. Reactive nitrogen is building in great pools in air, soil and water throughtout the biosphere. 
					  
                                   	</li>
    <li><b>What we can do.</b> <blockquote> "We need to talk about nitrogen deposition, to raise awareness of its causes and
consequences, to agree on solutions, and to work together to integrate these solutions into policy and practice now .  <a href="http://www.plantlife.org.uk/application/files/1614/9086/5868/We_need_to_talk_Nitrogen_webpdf2.pdf">We need to talk about Nitrogen</a></blockquote>
 </li>
  </ul>
  <br><br>

<section id="Box14">
<h2>Day 14 DWC: 2017-04-14 Good Friday</h2>
</section>
<h3>Easter Bunnies and a Golden Egg</h3>


<p>
In a a virtual world of medieval fantasy  behind some shrubby trees beyond  the glistening white  castellations of royal perimeter walls two adventurers, one in a graceful green outfit, the other a cabbage cape,  came upon a large agouti rabbit. Lolloping around rather comically and obviously confident he'd be  too great a prize for a poachers pie a party zone had emerged and his smaller kindred, enjoying themselves darted  skittishly, leaping playful in the pixel light.  
</p>
<p>
The large  comical old rabbit needed help with making eggs for Easter.   A rocky cavernous looking rabbit hole  was a portal and entering just a short arrival at an island surrounded by a still blue sea.  Hazy sunshine and white mist blurred  horizons.  This was a peaceful haven. 
</p>
<p>
A conversation with another rabbit and a swinging descent by rope into a cave.
</p>
<p>
The walls were smoothly sculpted with a clay like texture, crumbly but with beads of moisture here and there it appeared ideal for tunnelling.  Could this be one of those legendary mud dungeons of yore?
</p>
<p>
A strange array of scents and warm aromas wafted by.  Intense, enticing, ehhanced and imbibed with complex strangeness and unmistakeably chocolate. A hint of fishyness, some spice, a zesty lemony and tropical banana. This certainly smelled like a chocolate cavern, though with dim lighting it was hard to be certain.  
</p>
<p>
A golden rabbit hopped around looking somewhat overwhelmed.  He new where everything was and directed the bemused friends to larder shelves and crates. Egg moulds, a lovely old stempunk stove and plenty of colourful wrapping designs meant getting the job done went fairly smoothly.
</p>
<p>
The flavour of the eggs was pretty weird, spicy and fish and salted.  Eventually after making each egg carefully then precariously climbing up and down the rope, though fashioned as requested and ready to ship the Easter Bunny rejected each and every one. The eggs would not do for the customers, the flavours would be unpopular so he rudely hurled the helpers half way across the kingdom into a distant sea.  
</p>
<p>
This seemed suspiciously like a ploy.  Especially as the greedy rabbit had so voraciously eaten each egg  as it was presented to him.  Still they had not set out to be judgemental, just agreed to help with a task. Though one of the companions did for a moment wistfully recall a perfect golden egg, banana flavoured, that he'd been sure would be a hit.
</p>
<p>
Heading back while somewhat disgruntled by this lack of appreciation for their careful attention to detail they still hoped some small reward might be given for all the effort. It was worth the trek.  The rabbit grudgingly awarded colourful easter egg shaped helmets.  Though not without a reminder that this was purely an act of generosity on his part as there had in fact been no prior contractual agreement to the arrangements so he was under no obligation whatsoever.
</p>
