<section id="Box12">
<h2>Day 12 DWC: 2017-04-12 Wednesday</h2>
</section>

<h3>Have you lost your dog?</h3>

<h5>Road to nowhere</h5>


<p>
The lane gently dips away from the grassy junction.  The direction is due west so the sun, climbing higher now is to the left making half the lane concealed in the mottled shade of a neat shoulder high machine cut hedge of hazel and hawthorn. The other half is in full sun, reflecting and radiating warmth and vibrant colours with fresh spring greens emergent from the coppery russet litter of bracken and mouse coloured twiggery in verge and hedge.  
<br><br>
Amongst the greenery the creamy flutter of a butterfly with orange tip wings darts this way and that. Then the red and orange velveteen of a darker canvassed peacock insect gliding blinks.  Its large round eyes,  are pure azure with glints of eyeball white and rimmed seductively with kohl.  It leads the way settling purposefully on tarmac earth or leaf.  Outstretched wings double as finely decorated solar panels.
<br><br>
Sloping contoured upwards south west and in the dappled shade of widely spreading hedge trees a lush pasture.  Three horses, two brown and shiny cropping sward, one muddy oatmeal leans his tail against a chestnut post and rail. Sitting on the fence he maintains a steady swinging motion back and forth, his eyes half closed it seems  he inwardly  recites a mantra. And two brown cows one gently grazes the other sits legs tucked under resting in the lee of a hedge but with  head up quietly 
watchful.
<br><br>
An elderly couple with walking sticks are heading eastwards with a skinny grizzled black dog.  As we pass he smiles, his eyes are dim and his collar and leash loose as his body curves and sways a snakey motion that wriggles his tail.  Cheerfully and in mildly curious way we exchange greetings and  good'ays, then with a quizzical look the old man asks me. "Have you lost your dog?"

</p>

<p>With a little inspiration from this David Byrne song.<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8SSPnRK2Ads">... Road to Nowhere</a></p>

