<section id="Box11">
<h2>Day 11 DWC: 2017-04-11 Tuesday</h2>
</section>

<h3>Mindful Walking</h3>

<h5>New England Lane in Spring</h5>

<p>Morning sunshine has brought hundreds of tiny spiders out, they run across the tufty grass in all directions as the dew dries across a flood meadow of the brooks. Next to an old pollarded white willow at a confluence of streams beside a footbridge and in the middle of the footpath are the charcoal remains of a bonfire with the cut off base of a slightly melted traffic cone in the centre. Charred sticks, discarded into the stream jostle and bob between the banks under the bridge. Blackthorn petals drifting from a dense thicket strew the path, settling softly on the grey ashes and floating on the water. Fluttering and stuck they outline the shape of an orb web.</p>

<p>Across another footbridge under the arch of an ancient ivy clad sallow branch resting its top in a sunny field, white and delicate stitchwort flowers mingle with grass tussocks, there&#39;s a maroon leaved patch of pink dead nettles next to purple sprouting ground ivy and bold bright sunshine discs of many petalled dandelions lie flat against the smooth well walked baked mud. There&#39;s a dandelion clock standing tall totally transformed, pristine, inviting someone to pick it and blow its parachute seeds spinning into the sky. The sky is half blue half diffused gossamer white clouds which swirly smeared don&#39;t seem to know which way to go. Flaming gorse and tree tracery decked with tiny fresh leaves make patterns of exquisite intricacy. Birdsong everywhere. A kestrel hovering over his favourite spot just for the fun of it, or maybe practice.</p>

<p>Up a steep hill the tarmac lane is busy with cars. Its steep banks are crowded with primroses, celandines, violets and anemones. Near the top a wild orchid, many flowered, magenta bright, with a pointy top and dusky spots on its broad leaves. Then all these little bees, there are no plants on this part of bank, the soil is dry, dusty grey and crumbly. Its steep, almost cliff like in a miniature way and the little bees are buzzing around busily in its warm sheltered sun pocket. They are black and shiny with tiny grey tufts at the base of their legs. Round a corner the lane plunges into the deep shade of a clump of pine trees on a tump, their trunks concealed by deep green shaggy yews. Overhead noisy rooks caw and cackle croakily to each other, jackdaws occasionally interjecting with some more lively opinions.</p>

<p>Eventually I get there. A black topped white wooden sign post in a triangle of lush grass. Three ways, each wooden sign points directions with neat black letters and distance to villages in miles. New England Lane has no distance marked. It starts here.</p>

