<section id="Box9">
<h2>Day 9 DWC: 2017-04-09 Sunday</h2>
</section>

<h3>Three things I like about being in Nature.</h3>

<h5>Fresh Air</h5>

<p>Natural air filling the lungs educating the sense of smell and taste, awakening and oxygenating tiny blood vessels webbing skin. Each perambulation of flexing and stretching tendons over uneven but soft mulching leaves and hummocky grass Breathing a salty iodine infused sea breeze or a woodland&#39;s blended scents of lichen, moss and rotting bark suffuses the senses with a library of outdoor recognmition. Can be disturbing to approach busy roads or animal farms as the contrast becomes much more apparent.</p>

<h5>The sky and clouds</h5>

<p>Sunsets and cumulonimbus. The green flash that comes at the sun&#39;s point of descent into the horizon is something I&#39;d like to see. An unpredictable event but one that could be a phenomenal surprise. I once looked directly upwards when I noticed some really high clouds showing irridescence and was intrigued to see un upside down rainbow. It turned out to be a circumvenical arc.</p>

<h5>Soil</h5>

<p>The stuff that all the plants grow in. A dynamic recycling system filled with nutrients and decay.<br />
Some of the words from miriam-webster.com/thesaurus highlight a problematic association with pollution indeed, generally negative words. Scum, sewage, sewerage, slime, sludge, swill; dross, dust [British], garbage, junk, litter, refuse, rubbish, scrap, trash, waste; soot; dinginess, dirtiness, dustiness, filthiness, foulness, griminess, grubbiness, nastiness, squalidness, uncleanliness, uncleanness.<br />
A bit about the origin from thesaurus.com indicates the problem goes back a long way. soil early 13c., &quot;to defile or pollute with sin,&quot; from O.Fr. souillier &quot;to foul or make dirty,&quot; originally &quot;to wallow,&quot; from souil &quot;tub, wild boar&#39;s wallow, pigsty,&quot; either from L. solium &quot;tub for bathing, seat,&quot; or from L. suculus &quot;little pig,&quot; from sus &quot;pig.&quot; Meaning &quot;to make dirty, begrime&quot; is attested from c.1300. This is the sense of the noun in archaic night-soil.</p>

<section id="Box8">
<h2>Day 8 DWC: 2017-04-08 Saturday</h2>
</section>

<h3>Terminology, acronyms and jargon.</h3>

<p>One of the things I found fairly quickly when I started learning to code was the amount of unfamiliar language being used to explain the process. Each new step brings with it new words to describe what it is going on.</p>

<h5>Syntax and semantics.</h5>

<p>The difference between syntax and semantics came up quite early on and has reinforced itself in my mind as being an important distinction to be aware of. Structure and meaning is another way to put it.<br />
<br />
There is: How to do things. What with?<br />
<br />
There are: Reasons to do things. Why?<br />
<br />
Coding for me is a shuttling between these two pillars. A polarisation that becomes blended with time and activity. The yin and yang symbol is an iconic representation of this simple process. As one element swirls and blends with the other so the seed of its opposite is born in itself. Starting with the simplicity of binary, complexity emerges. Syntax can be reassuringly unambiguous, semantics more elusive. You can make a box with syntax then use semantics to explore the meaning of being inside or outside of the box. Or you can pack all your meaning in a box to take with you on a journey. Learning to code is like putting what you need in a box and having something useful to unpack when you get there. What book would you take to read on a desert island?</p>

<h5>HTML</h5>

<p>Hyper Text Mark-up Language.<br />
How to name a document that computers recognise through a browser on the internet.<br />
<br />
.html</p>

<h5>Understanding</h5>

<p>To get it, is to grasp the meaning. To get the message. To communicate is to convey meaning. An adventure or a quest? Adventuring is a stepping out, questing is to seek for answers. There is writing, and there&#39;s reading. Two sides of a coin. Heads or tails? Breath out breath in. Meaning written into the code goes into the computer to be transported, converted, translated, stored. Accessed, read, acted upon relayed, delayed. Lost.</p>

<h5>Recursive acronym</h5>

<p>Comes back to haunt you devoid of meaning. A wildebeest of the mind. Awe strikes as only signs of human ingenuity catching the senses do. Syntactic structure can be like Stonehenge unmistakeable and bold yet utterly unfathomable in its mysterious landscape and yet, its meaning knows no bounds. Semantic. Those pillars and lintels, open portals to the air and sky of sunrise and moonset. A framework for understanding the nature of all time. Set in stone. Carefully chosen stone at that. Bluestone and Sarsen on a bed of whitest chalk.</p>

<h5>Song for Saturday</h5>

<p>Feeling like I&#39;ve been sitting still too long I put on some headphones and find some rocking beats in my Google play library to loosen up. I choose Leaving Home for the association the words make with getting out of my comfort zone and thinking in and outside of boxes, a recurring theme. The song is from on the Exit Planet Dust album by the Chemical Brothers so the next song is In dust we trust then Playground For A Wedgeless Firm followed by A Song for The Siren (live). The tracks are all jumbled up so liking the rhythmic contrasting beats I start again and listen to the whole album straight through in the right order. .<br />
<br />
The last song with its combination of clipped harsh electronica, sawing synths, brushed and crashing cymbals and velvety bass line complimented with bubbling arcady and faintly Berber bazaar rhythms, spacey echoes and sweetly sung harmonically layered vocal tones of lyrical astuteness meandering over a rather laboured repetitivenes particularly resonates so I listen to it a couple of times.<br />
<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CZIXItHqTLI">- Alive Alone, The Chemical Brothers.</a><br />
If that link doesn&#39;t work it can be found at the bottom of<a href="http://www.thechemicalbrothers.com/history"> The Chemical Brothers History </a> a nice scrolling parralax page through their back catalogue.</p>

