<section id="Box7">
<h2>Day 7 DWC: 2017-04-07 Friday</h2>
</section>



<h3>Yesterday, today and tomorrow.</h3>

<p>Yesterday I tried to. sort out the calendar box for this months writing. I&#39;m still enthusiastic about the idea of making my own streak box and think it is doable at this stage in my adventures with code. Unfortunately I made a proper cats cradle of the whole thing yesterday and although finally managed to get the all important red x&#39;s inside the daily flexboxes, rearranging the boxes into a sensible grid involved much failed trial and error.</p>

<p>At least I had written a decent size block of text to add so I copied that into an HTML document I&#39;d made the day before.</p>

<p>The CSS calendar was made in a fresh document separately to be clear about what was going on. So I pasted that into the head of the HTML. This seemed to look decipherable to a non-coder but, or perhaps it would be better to say, UI not that smooth and UX not great - I imagine? (Thinking about the U part but that&#39;s another story) - There was much more I would have preferred to achieve with it and so it just looked unfinished, work in progress. With the limited time available I thought I&#39;d enhance this appearance a touch by adding dashed borders.</p>

<p>Looked forward to seeing the how it rendered on a desktop PC, uploading to the web and running it through the w3c validator to check for errors. There were quite a few, which was interesting. An invisible character in the doctype declaration for one, and some stray tags, but more usefully it made plainer to me my inexperience with things in the head of the document.</p>

<p>Made corrections from the list of errors highlighted by w3c in C-Panel editor. This went quite smoothly and it was helpful to see where I&#39;d been going wrong. But apart from the numbered line and column location making it quickly navigable, the error messages themselves and the explanitroy pages I looked to for reference were a bit over my head.</p>

<p>Was quite pleased when the document finally showed no errors. So when I had a look on my phone after I&#39;d left the PC I was dismayed to find the calendar boxes all over the place again.</p>

<p>So today I&#39;m going to:<br />
<br />
* Start again with just an HTML document.<br />
<br />
* Find out a bit more about stuff that goes in the head of the HTML document.<br />
<br />
* Understand better the difference between markup and markdown and when it&#39;s appropriate to use them.<br />
<br />
* Skim through a C-Panel tutorial app I downloaded on the phone.<br />
<br />
* Make the reader/text panel narrower on desktop for easier reading.<br />
<br />
* Have another go at making the CSS calendar grid.<br />
<br />
Tomorrow is another day, I&#39;ll see how this one goes first. Ok just realised its Friday! Writing this means I&#39;ve completed a whole week, yay! So tomorrow is another week too. I&#39;ve enjoyed writing so far, I try to bring along a playful attitude having fun with the process and prepared for some tragic humour now and then. The writing part has proved easier than preparing the document which I thought I had ready. Nothing like giving things a try for showing up strengths and weaknesses - so cheerfully looking forward to the next leg of the challenge.</p>

