<section id="Box6">
<h2>Day 6 DWC: 2017-04-06 Thursday</h2>
</section>



<h3>Meditation, stoicism and insight</h3>

<blockquote>&quot;There are two things that must be rooted out in human beings&mdash;arrogant opinion and mistrust. Arrogant opinion expects that there is nothing further needed, and mistrust assumes that under the torrent of circumstance there can be no happiness.&rdquo; &mdash;EPICTETUS, DISCOURSES</blockquote>

<blockquote>&quot;Remember, if there is one core teaching at the heart of this philosophy, it&rsquo;s that we&rsquo;re not as smart and as wise as we&rsquo;d like to think we are.&quot; - April 7th The Daily Stoic, by Ryan Halliday</blockquote>

<p>After meditating for an hour on waking I read a page of The Daily Stoic (on editing I notice it was the wrong day) and now I&#39;m going to write about it. As I seek to make a habit of the practice of writing this seems like a good sequence. Last year I did a MOOC on Mindfulness made by Future Learn and Monash University in Australia. I made a deliberate effort to communicate on the forums, engaging with other learners to share the experience. Although it took quite some time to do this on top of following the video lectures and delving into the various readings offered, to read about others thoughts along the way and to share some of my own was valuable. Meditating is not always easy and pleasant and it can be reassuring to find the same applies to others. To being with I certainly found it a challenge.<br />
<br />
Once I found I could actually sit still for five minutes to a guided body scan my mind and thoughts started to argue and object to the guide. Particularly training myself like a puppy on a mat. I could understand the rationale behind it, a gentle approach to discipline but was bothered by a rather minimalist and stereotyped advertising image. All very pure and clean. My experience with dogs is somewhat less sterile, muddy paws jumping up, shaking wet fur over furniture and rolling in smelly things. Staying on track with the discipline though, I have in the past succeeded with dog training. Border collie sheepdogs are easy, they pay attention and learn quickly. When I thought about a puppy to train for the mindfulness exercise it was a labrador, perhaps as these are more steady in their temperament, but in hindsight I don&#39;t know why I didn&#39;t pick a collie which is where my experience lies.<br />
<br />
Collies are sharp and respond instantly once they&#39;ve got the what you&#39;re asking of them. But establishing obedience in the first place was the thing I was objecting to, and I think this is the main purpose of the exercise. This is about establishing trust. And the only thing I&#39;m being asked to trust is myself. To ask the puppy to sit quietly on a mat is to convince him that this is an appropriate way to conduct himself. To learn manners and patience will be a good thing for his future prospects. I&#39;d be asking him to trust me.<br />
<br />
I eventually stopped arguing and gave it a try and sitting quietly focusing on the breath is all there is to it really.<br />
<br />
The benefits came through with the process of letting thoughts come and go, arise and fade. Acknowledging without getting too hooked up. Recognising my own internal dialogue and being OK with it.<br />
<br />
I managed to establish a five minute mindful practice every day and kept it up for a couple of months then let it slip. Before I realised a month had gone by without any meditations. This was all the more apparent because I had started using Insight Timer, an app on my phone, to time and log my sessions. For the month of December there weren&#39;t any.<br />
<br />
January brought with it a fresh resolve and I joined 365 days of meditation group on Insight Timer. This time I listened to guided meditations, whilst keeping up my own five minute daily practice. I promised myself just five minutes a day EVERY day for a year and Insight Timer provided the opportunity to share this journey with other people as well as keeping a record and a log if I felt like it. I find checking back on my progress now and again is encouraging and motivating.<br />
<br />
At the same time, the beginning of January I started reading the Daily Stoic. Very compatible with this daily practice theme. The ebook is set out with a page to read each day with simple yet profound philosophical observations. Daily quotations from Seneca, Marcus Aurelius and Epictetus with short commentaries on how these ideas may relate to us right now are great little primers for navigating daily life whilst considering the human condition and its and effect on the world.<br />
<br />
Today&#39;s Stoic reading is a perfect reminder of what&#39;s needed to achieve the balance required for creative endeavour. Trust and humility can be found by doing, getting things right and getting things wrong. Combined with meditation the stoic way is helping me to access the insight necessary to create, a sweet spot between trust and humility.<br />
<br />
just ... keep calm and carry on.<br />
