I wanted to sort out the calender I tried to make at the top of the page with flexbix and it wasn&#39;t happening. I thought I&#39;d have a go with grid as this sounds like it might be suitable for the task but a couple of hours reading through articles I&#39;d saved in pocket and trying out some examples I saw on codepen resulted in confirming that the browsers I&#39;m trying it out I don&#39;t support it yet.<br />
<br />
So I decided to have another go with flexbox. I started a new file with some boxes I made a little while levago<br />
<br />
Putting them in one flex container and trying out different selectors. Sometimes the process feels slow but it is absorbing and when I&#39;m making things like this and tweaking ng how things work eventually it sinks in. For learning I find css much easier than the programming languages &#39;proper&#39; although it still works, if the syntax is wrong I shows up visually with things going crazy jumbled up. This is a good pointer to the exacting nature of code. One mistake I made which causedcthe boxes to go all over the place was a curly brace facing the wrong way..<br />
<br />
Sometimes mistakes lead to interesting consewueces<br />
<br />
And in this respect is quite fun. Trying to do something I want on the other hand still takes a painfully long time, especially offline. Although I have lots of resources on the phone, from nding them, particularly if they&#39;re PDFs can take a frustratingly long time. Much faster searching things up on. Google when connected.. Still, I think I do remember better the slow way, and amvmore likely to try things out from memory. Practicing as with this writing task is important. Recognising patterns and getting comfortable playing around with them.<br />
