<section id="Box4">
<h2>Day 4 DWC: 2017-04-04 Tuesday</h2>
</section>



<h3>Packed in a dairy that handles nuts: mindfulness and packaging.</h3>

<p>This morning I got up and went to make myself a coffee. Eating a spoonful of basic lemon curd to satisfy a craving for sweetness which I haven&#39;t yet completely overcome since giving up sugar in coffee I perused the words on the packaging of the plastic tub I&#39;d put some instant coffee in the night before. Having sought out a saved handy tub that looked suitable I&#39;d &quot;borrowed&quot; a generous cupful from my daughters full jar to put off a dreaded shopping trip for another day.<br />
<br />
Preparing for my mindful session and in the present with a curious eye for reading everything that looks like a word I scanned the label on this tub. Stickers, slogans, attention grabbing headlines, social media icons, humorous puns, accurate measurements and statistics, email, slomail and website contact addresses, recycling advice, proud achievement declarations, international standards observation, a barcode, tasteful design with carefully chosen fonts and colours, associated animals, their shape used as placeholders for words conveying community spirit, the product itself an international delicacy prepared by gourmet expert chefs with live fresh delicious bionutrients.<br />
<br />
I could go deeper but the reassuring &quot;suitable for vegetarians&quot; combined with a stencilled union jack cow and the words &quot;packed in a dairy that handles nuts.&quot; Is a reminder. I have a lazy habit of taking care to read labels formed when I became vegetarian in my early twenties. I made this decision because I couldn&#39;t feel alright about animals being put through the horrible process of meat production on an industrial scale. Animals are conscious, they have feelings. To me it&#39;s just wrong, thoughtless, disrespectful and cruel to treat them in this way. But abstaining is not easy, as avoiding too much sugar or salt or eating anything without palm oil in it isn&#39;t. The onus is on yourself when you can read, the information is all there if you care to calculate the optimum quantities.<br />
<br />
It all kind of defies common sense and I do think there is such a thing.<br />
<br />
I&#39;ve always been interested in packaging and In a lot of ways I can see a similar process with web design. One of the reasons I&#39;m doing this challenge is for the sake of generating content. Having learned a little about coding and bumping up against ipsum lorum est a few times it&#39;s time to consider content.<br />
<br />
It just occurred to me that this packaging is not really food but a form of entertainment. Cue use the tub as suggested, I did for that sake of a cup of coffee. Now I feel like I should be vegan.<br />
<br />
Mindfulness is helping me think and observe. I have long considered and read books about it and admire the creativity, aesthetics, calmness and clarity, things like zen and haiku and the mirror mind. But meditating as a practice confounded me. I&#39;m way too fidgety to sit still like that. After about a minute I would rather just lie down and go to sleep.<br />
<br />
