<section id="Box3">
<h2>Day 3: 30 DWC 2017-04-03 Monday</h2>
</section>


<h3>Tools for writing</h3>

<p>Today I&#39;m writing about the tools I&#39;m using for this project. Making the task as streamlined as possible has been at the back of my mind in order to avoid procrastination and distraction. The writing itself I am doing on an Android One plus One phone using Writer app with a white background and a Swiftkey keyboard that&#39;s black with white letters. Although I have a powerpack backup for the phone the battery life is very good so I can easily pick up the phone and write offline anywhere.<br />
<br />
I can type fairly quickly with my thumb and although the autocorrect/ suggestion thing sometimes overrides what I want to say and I often press v&#39;s instead of the space bar, using the phone is a very effective and convenient tool.<br />
<br />
I intend to write the whole piece without editing so as not to interrupt the flow of thinking, then briefly skim over what I have written for grammar, spelling and typo errors. When the first draft is complete and after checking I&#39;ll go to Code Editor the app I have chosen for phone coding, and make a new page from a copy and paste of the one I made yesterday. Next I&#39;ll copy what I&#39;ve written in writer and paste it into the new file.<br />
<br />
Using the phone for coding has been a major leap forward in my coding journey. A few months ago I decided to try using code editors on the phone so I could practice anytime offline. To start with this seemed really fiddly but after a while I got the hang of it and now I usually write code first on the phone and actually find it harder using a keyboard and PC. There is something about using a handheld touchscreen which seems to be less of a barrier to the thinking process than a conventional keyboard and screen. This goes well with my thoughts about Responsive web design and mobile first. With the increase in mobile and handheld devices the phone itself feels like a good place to start.<br />
<br />
When the writing is in code editor I&#39;ll preview it in several browsers, Chrome Brave, Ghostery, Firefox and Opera, and make some adjustments to the markup. This is an opportunity to learn a bit more about HTML and perhaps try some new things and also have another go at getting more more practice with CSS flexbox . I&#39;ve got HTML and css apps for reference, as well as a substantial phone library to refer to if need be.<br />
<br />
Interruptions completely demolish my attempts to focus on the task.<br />
<br />
When I get to a wifi connection I send the HTML file to myself as an email attachment via gmail. When on desktop PC I open the file in Notepad++ and upload.</p>



<section id="Box2">
<h2>Day 2 DWC: 2017-04-02 Sunday</h2>
</section>



<h3>Down by the stream ...</h3>

<p>Its Sunday and its spring. A gorgeous day, blue skies puffy clouds a warm and gentle breeze. Birds singing, chiff-chaff, robin, wren. Starry wood anemones deck the dappled shade of the woodland floor, a few bluebells emerge from a dark green carpet of glossy blades. The air is laced with the scent of primroses.<br />
<br />
Flora has visited. I can imagine a beautiful goddess casting her blessings over the countryside.<br />
<br />
Reality and imagination. It feels good to observe reality and then let the mind respond with stories.<br />
<br />
I do want to write but I hesitate. Transfixed. It&#39;s like going to a supermarket when you&#39;re hungry, there is just too much choice. I guess its getting into the right frame of mind. Once I get going it&#39;ll be OK. The words will flow.<br />
<br />
I&#39;ve had a few ideas for what to write about. My coding journey. Cognitive dissonance. A fascination with what&#39;s difficult. Once down by the stream ... The magic of the machine. Anxiety, illusion. I&#39;m reading Yuval Harari&#39;s book Sapiens and I find his historians view of humanity offers new perspectives on some things that I&#39;ve found troubling for a long time. The way we believe in stories is characteristic and what those stories are has consequences.<br />
<br />
What is a meta narrative? All the time time I&#39;m learning new things, asking new questions. Filling in gaps and it doesn&#39;t seem to be getting easier.<br />
<br />
Follow your passion - I question this. People are always saying it, asking what it is. I think I did that already. I kept horses for years. I loved them their beauty, their affection. Their strength and gracefulness. They lifted my spirits above the mud and mucking out, dreary weather and filling haynets. There was a rhythm to it that felt timeless and connected. Earthed in a way that I understood when all was well with the world. Set fair my sister called it after finishing a morning routine when the ponies were all out contentedly grazing in paddocks and everything was cleaned.<br />
<br />
Yes I suppose horses were a passion, but not now. I still miss them terribly, its only just over a year since the last one&#39;s horsey spirit departed. They were my friends. They could be crabby, they could be frightening and often got me worried. Keeping horses was a huge challenge that teased out of me resourcefulness and tenacity I didn&#39;t know I had. It also gave me an enormous appreciation of other living beings and the world we share. They taught me a lot about feelings and emotion which brings me back to the passion thing. Its generally not a good thing for horses to get excited, they may look impressive and wow people but its much nicer when they&#39;re calm and settled.<br />
<br />
... of conciousness</p>



<section id="Box1">
<h3>Day 1 DWC: 2017-04-01 Saturday</h3>
